                        <p>Key performance strategies include code splitting, lazy loading, image optimization, and efficient caching mechanisms. Tools like Webpack, Vite, and Parcel have made it easier to implement these optimizations automatically during the build process.</p>
                    </section>

                    <section id="security">
                        <h2>Security Best Practices</h2>
                        <p>Security in web development requires a multi-layered approach, addressing vulnerabilities at every level of the application stack. From input validation to secure authentication, developers must be vigilant about potential security threats.</p>
                        <p>Common security concerns include Cross-Site Scripting (XSS), SQL injection, Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF), and insecure direct object references. Modern frameworks provide built-in protections against many of these threats, but developers must still understand the underlying principles.</p>
                        <p>Implementing Content Security Policy (CSP), using HTTPS everywhere, and regularly updating dependencies are fundamental practices that every web application should follow. Security is not a one-time consideration but an ongoing responsibility.</p>
